      "speaker": "Guest",
      "text": "The entire journey is like an arranged marriage. In childhood, you're told your 'spouse' is a job. You have to prepare for it. You spend years preparing. You go to college with a predetermined idea of what job you'll get. In the third year, when you realize there might be a challenge, you start beautifying yourself—taking online courses, learning new skills—like preparing for marriage. And somehow, you get a job. It's like everyone gets married eventually. But this script doesn't account for sudden disruptions like AI."
    },
    {
      "topic": "The Impact of Sudden Layoffs and Lack of Preparedness",
      "speaker": "Guest",
      "text": "When companies like Google, Oracle, and Block started massive layoffs citing AI, senior engineers posted on LinkedIn that they gave 12 years to the company and weren't even informed properly. They were just told to submit their laptop and not come to their desk. There's no script for this situation. No book tells you what to do when you're suddenly fired after following the entire script perfectly. This is one of the biggest challenges we're facing right now."
