      "speaker": "Guest",
      "text": "At PayPal, there was a pattern—layoffs happened every February. We used to joke that they'd come with trucks and take people to factories. They'd only interview 6-pointers because they knew 9-pointers would leave after a month. The real problem is that companies aren't doing this because they're struggling. Google is doing well. Oracle is doing well. They're doing it because the stock market rewards it. When a company announces layoffs, their stock price goes up. So now more companies are firing people just to show they're optimizing, even if there's no real impact."
    },
    {
      "topic": "The Emotional and Practical Impact of Sudden Firings",
      "speaker": "Guest",
      "text": "When you don't know if you'll have a job in two months, you can't give 100% to your work. You're preparing for interviews elsewhere, worried about your family's expenses, and stressed about the uncertainty. This creates a FOMO—fear of missing out—where people are constantly switching jobs. I've worked at almost all top tech companies, and I was always in a switching mentality. But when I look back, I realize I was just chasing what society told me to chase, not what I actually needed."
    },
    {
      "topic": "The Importance of Continuous Learning and Flexibility",
      "speaker": "Guest",
      "text": "The key to surviving in today's world is flexibility and continuous learning. If you think you've learned one thing and that's your entire life, you will become obsolete. Every day, I spend at least 30 minutes to an hour learning new concepts because I live with the fear that a 20-year-old fresh graduate might replace me, especially in this age of AI. If you don't uplift yourself, you'll be left behind. The approach should be: I have to be flexible, I'm open to change, and change is the only constant."
    },
    {
      "topic": "Three Jobs That Will Disappear",
      "speaker": "Guest",
      "text": "First, operational service-based jobs where you maintain records, write documentation, and create content will completely disappear. Second, entry-level coding jobs where you write simple code or APIs will be depleted. Third, if you don't have a learning attitude and think you can coast on one skill forever, you will be fired. These three categories will be hit the hardest by automation and AI."
