    },
    {
      "topic": "The Need for a New Script for Society",
      "speaker": "Guest",
      "text": "We need to write a new script for society. The old script of Crack, Switch, and EMI needs to be replaced with Depth (specialization), Build (creating something), and Compound (long-term growth). Instead of just switching jobs, we should focus on building something meaningful. Instead of living on EMI, we should think about compounding our skills and wealth. This new script is needed so that the next generation is ready for the AI age."
    },
    {
      "topic": "The Role of Top Institutions in the AI Era",
      "speaker": "Guest",
      "text": "The responsibility lies with our top institutions. They need to teach what's relevant today and what will be relevant in the future. They need to focus on specialization, not generalization. They need to bring quantum computing into their curriculum. They need to teach hands-on skills that are actually used in the industry. Right now, most institutions are stuck in the past, and that's why we're not producing the right talent for the AI revolution."
    },
    {
      "topic": "India's Challenge in the Global AI Race",
      "speaker": "Guest",
      "text": "Today, AI is dominated by the US. ChatGPT is a US company. Gemini is Google, a US company. Grok is a US company. Claude is a US company. Where are we? We're still talking about our achievements, but we haven't built foundational models. We don't have our own compute power. We're still just wrappers around existing models. If we don't build our own foundational models, this will be the last generation that has the opportunity for wealth creation. After that, we'll be permanent slaves to the technology created by others."
    },
    {
      "topic": "The False Narrative Around Indian AI Summit",
      "speaker": "Guest",
      "text": "Recently, there was a big AI summit in India, and we're calling it the biggest event for the Global South. But 99% of the people showcasing their work are just wrappers around existing models. We haven't built our own foundation. We haven't expressed our compute power. We only have a few models to talk about. Sarvam is ahead, but we're still nowhere close. The US is leading, China has some models like DeepSeek and Qwen. Europe has Mistral. India is lagging behind, and that's a big challenge."
    },
    {
      "topic": "The Importance of Hands-On Experience in Interviews",
      "speaker": "Guest",
      "text": "When I interviewed at Amazon, they gave me four coding rounds. These weren't theoretical questions—they were real, challenging problems. The difference between solving a problem at home on your comfortable couch and solving it in an interview with pressure is huge. You have to prepare for the actual conditions. You can't just take online courses and expect to crack interviews at top companies. You need to practice under pressure, in uncomfortable situations, at the right time of day."
    },
    {
      "topic": "The Difference Between Service-Based and Product-Based Companies",
      "speaker": "Guest",
      "text": "Service-based companies like TCS and Infosys assume you know nothing and train you for six months. They deploy you to clients and expect minimal work. Product-based companies like Amazon, Google, and Microsoft expect you to be ready from day one. They're looking for people who can solve novel problems, design systems at scale, and adapt to new technologies. The hiring bar is completely different. Service companies filter by GPA; product companies filter by actual problem-solving ability."
    },
    {
      "topic": "The Corruption in Placement Systems",
      "speaker": "Guest",
      "text": "I've seen something very controversial but true: some of the biggest universities have their placement heads taking bribes from mass recruiters. They literally carry gold coins in their pockets and give them to HR heads to build relationships. During Diwali, they send their entire team across India with pockets full of gold coins to build these relationships. This is why certain colleges always get placements from certain companies, regardless of student quality. It's a systemic corruption that's been normalized."
    },
    {
      "topic": "The False Promises of Private Colleges",
      "speaker": "Guest",
      "text": "Private colleges advertise that their students get 1 crore packages, but this is misleading. Out of 10,000 computer science students, maybe one or two get such packages. The rest are just paying fees. These colleges use flashy marketing and social media to attract students with false promises. They might have one legitimate placement, but they advertise it as if everyone gets it. Students should be very careful about these false narratives."
    },
    {
      "topic": "Why Degrees Still Matter Despite System Flaws",
      "speaker": "Guest",
      "text": "Even though the education system is broken, degrees still matter. You can't get into MIT for a master's without a bachelor's degree. You can't apply for certain government jobs without a degree. The system is flawed, but we can't just abolish it overnight. Change has to happen gradually. We need to improve how degrees are executed, not eliminate them. The solution is to make the four years of engineering more relevant and practical, not to replace it with online certificates."
    },
    {
      "topic": "The Generalization Problem in Engineering Education",
      "speaker": "Guest",
      "text": "In engineering, 30-40% of a computer science student's time is spent on irrelevant subjects—biology labs, physics labs, carpentry. If a student wants to become an AI engineer, why are they forced to memorize inorganic chemistry reactions? This is the core problem. We need to move toward specialization. Students should be able to focus on their chosen field from day one, not waste time on subjects they'll never use."
    },
    {
      "topic": "The Quantum Computing Revolution",
      "speaker": "Guest",
      "text": "Quantum computing is going to disrupt everything. Today's computers work on bits—zero or one. Quantum computers work on qubits, which can be zero, one, or both simultaneously. This means infinite possibilities in the same system. A problem that takes years to solve today could be solved in weeks with quantum. All our current passwords and encryption will become useless. Everything we've written will need to be rewritten. Three to four years from now, everyone will be talking about quantum AI, not just AI."
    },
    {
